## Recommended Fix

Replace the current blacklist pattern with a whitelist approach:

```php
// Current (VULNERABLE):
if (preg_match('#[\x00-\x1F\x7F\s]#u', $this->request['login'])) {
    $this->aErrors = [$GLOBALS['strInvalidUsername']];
}

// Recommended (SECURE):
if (empty($this->request['login']) || 
    strlen($this->request['login']) > 255 ||
    !preg_match('/^[a-zA-Z0-9._@-]+$/D', $this->request['login']) ||
    $this->request['login'] !== trim($this->request['login'])) {
    $this->aErrors = [$GLOBALS['strInvalidUsername']];
}
```

**Additional recommendations:**
1. Unicode normalization (NFC) before validation
2. Implement confusables detection
3. Log suspicious username patterns
4. Display hex representation in admin UI

